==English==

===Alternative forms===
* [[abs.]]

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|absence|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|absence|lang=fro}}, {{term|ausence|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|absentia|lang=la}}, from {{m|la|absēns||absent}}, present active participle of {{term|absum||I am away or absent|lang=la}}, from {{term|ab||from, away from|lang=la}} + {{term|sum||I am|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈæb.sn̩s/|/ˈæb.sn̩ts/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-absence.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# A state of being [[away]] or [[withdrawn]] from a place or from [[companionship]]; the period of being away. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{reference-book|editor=Brown, Lesley|title=The Shorter Oxford English Dictionary|origyear=1933|edition=5th|year=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford, UK|isbn =978-0-19-860575-7|pages=8|}}</ref>
#: {{usex|lang=en|'''Absence''' makes the heart grow fonder.}}
#* {{rfdate}} ''{{w|Epistle to the Phillipians|Phillipians}} 2:12''
#*: Not as in my presence only, but now much more in my '''absence'''.
# Failure to be present where one is expected, wanted, or needed; nonattendance; deficiency. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{usex|lang=en|He had an '''absence''' of enthusiasm.}}
#* {{rfdate}} - [[Kent]]
#*: In the '''absence''' of conventional law.
# [[lack|Lack]]; [[deficiency]]; [[nonexistence]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# [[inattention|Inattention]] to things present; [[abstraction]] (of mind). {{defdate|First attested in the early 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{usex|lang=en|'''absence''' of mind}}
#* {{rfdate}}, {{w|Joseph Addison}} (1672-1719)
#*: Reflecting on the little '''absences''' and distractions of mankind.
#* '''1824-1829?''', {{w|Walter Savage Landor|Walter Landor}}, ''{{w|Imaginary Conversations}}''
#*: To conquer that abstraction which is called '''absence'''.
# {{context|medical|lang=en}} Temporary loss or disruption of consciousness, with sudden onset and recovery, and common in epilepsy. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 20<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|fencing|lang=en}} Lack of contact between [[blade]]s.

